{"award_age":67.0,"bio_image":"full\/8ff4b87a01b11ceff1ec23a2cecc642778b07bd2.jpg","category":"Literature","country":"Sweden","date_of_birth":"1864-07-20T00:00:00.000Z","date_of_death":"1931-04-08T00:00:00.000Z","gender":"male","image_urls":["http:\/\/upload.wikimedia.org\/wikipedia\/commons\/thumb\/e\/e7\/Erik_Axel_Karlfeldt_1931.jpg\/220px-Erik_Axel_Karlfeldt_1931.jpg"],"link":"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Erik_Axel_Karlfeldt","mini_bio":"<p><b>Erik Axel Karlfeldt<\/b> (20 July 1864 \u2013 8 April 1931) was a <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Sweden\" title=\"Sweden\">Swedish<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Poet\" title=\"Poet\">poet<\/a> whose highly symbolist <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Poetry\" title=\"Poetry\">poetry<\/a> masquerading as regionalism was popular and won him the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Nobel_Prize_in_Literature\" title=\"Nobel Prize in Literature\">Nobel Prize in Literature<\/a> posthumously in 1931. It has been rumored that he had been offered, but declined, the award already in 1919.<sup id=\"cite_ref-1\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Erik_Axel_Karlfeldt#cite_note-1\"><span>[<\/span>1<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup> His unwillingness to accept the award might help explain why he remains the only posthumous winner of the Nobel Prize in Literature in the prize's history.<sup id=\"cite_ref-2\" class=\"reference\"><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Erik_Axel_Karlfeldt#cite_note-2\"><span>[<\/span>2<span>]<\/span><\/a><\/sup><\/p><p>Karlfeldt was born into a farmer's family in <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Karlbo\" title=\"Karlbo\">Karlbo<\/a>, in the province of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Dalarna\" title=\"Dalarna\">Dalarna<\/a>. Initially, his name was <i>Erik Axel Eriksson<\/i>, but he assumed his new name in 1889, wanting to distance himself from his father, who had suffered the disgrace of a criminal conviction. He studied at <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Uppsala_University\" title=\"Uppsala University\">Uppsala University<\/a>, simultaneously supporting himself by teaching school in several places, including <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Djursholms_samskola\" title=\"Djursholms samskola\">Djursholms samskola<\/a> in the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Stockholm\" title=\"Stockholm\">Stockholm<\/a> suburb of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Djursholm\" title=\"Djursholm\">Djursholm<\/a> and at a school for adults. After completing his studies, he held a position at the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Royal_Library_of_Sweden\" title=\"Royal Library of Sweden\" class=\"mw-redirect\">Royal Library of Sweden<\/a>, in Stockholm, for five years.<\/p><p>In 1904 Karlfeldt was elected a member of the <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Swedish_Academy\" title=\"Swedish Academy\">Swedish Academy<\/a> and held chair number 11. In 1905 he was elected a member of the Nobel Institute of the Academy, and, in 1907, of the Nobel Committee. In 1912 he was elected permanent secretary of the Academy, a position he held until his death.<\/p><p><a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Uppsala_University\" title=\"Uppsala University\">Uppsala University<\/a>, Karlfeldt's <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Alma_mater\" title=\"Alma mater\">alma mater<\/a>, awarded him the title of <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Doctor_of_Philosophy\" title=\"Doctor of Philosophy\">Doctor<\/a> <a href=\"http:\/\/en.wikipedia.org\/wiki\/Honoris_causae\" title=\"Honoris causae\" class=\"mw-redirect\">honoris causae<\/a> in 1917.<\/p>","name":"Erik Axel Karlfeldt","place_of_birth":"Karlbo,  Dalarna ,  Sweden","place_of_death":"Stockholm , Sweden","text":"Erik Axel Karlfeldt , Literature, 1931","year":1931.0}